SIMPLE: hanker
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hanker
<hw>Han"ker</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧"k⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hankered</conjf>
<pr>(-k⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hankering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prob. fr. <ets>hang</ets>; cf.
D. <ets>hunkeren</ets>, <ets>hengelen</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
long (for) with a keen appetite and uneasiness; to have a vehement
desire; -- usually with <xex>for</xex> or <xex>after</xex>; <as>as, to
<ex>hanker</ex> after fruit; to <ex>hanker</ex> after the diversions of
the town.</as></def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was <qex>hankering</qex> to join his friend.</q> <rj><qau>J. A.
Symonds.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To linger in expectation or with desire.</def>
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hankeringly</ent>⟦br⟧
